s Regulation: Liberal Democracy and Sexual Citizenship in Canada -- tHistory and Beyond -- tCommunity and Expertise in Canadian Democracy since 1920 -- tReckoning with the Realities of History: The Politics of White Supremacy and the Expansion of Settler Democracy in the Nineteenth and Early Twentieth Centuries -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMost Canadians assume they live under some form of democracy. Yet confusion about the meaning of the word and the limits of the people’s power obscures a deeper understanding. Constant Struggle looks for the democratic impulse in Canada’s past to deconstruct how the country became a democracy, if in fact it ever did.This volume asks what limits and contradictions have framed the nation’s democratization process, examining how democracy has been understood by those who have advocated for or resisted it and exploring key historical realities that have shaped it. Scholars from a range of disciplines tackle this elusive concept, suggesting that instead of looking for a simple narrative, we must be alert to the slower, untidier, and incomplete processes of democratization in Canada. Constant Struggle offers a renewed, sometimes unsettling depiction, stretching from studies of early Indigenous societies, through colonial North America and Confederation, into the twentieth century. Contributors reassess democracy in light of settler colonialism and white supremacy, investigate connections between capitalism and democracy, consider alternative conceptions of democracy from Canada’s past, and highlight the various ways in which the democratic ideal has been mobilized to advance particular visions of Canadian society.Demonstrating that Canada’s democratization process has not always been one that empowered the people, Constant Struggle questions traditional views of the relationship between democracy and liberalism in Canada and around the world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aDemocracyzCanadaxHistory. 0aDemocratizationzCanadaxHistory. 0aLiberalismzCanadaxHistory. 7aHISTORY / Canada / Pre-Confederation (to 1867).2bisacsh  aC B Macpherson.  aCanadian Confederation.  aGladston Murray.  aJoseph-Charles Tache.  acolonial democratization.  acorporations.  adebts.  ahuman rights.  aliberal.  aliberalism.  asettler.  awelfare state.  awhite supremacism.1 aDelâge, Denys, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrager, Ruth A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrittner, Colin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHalladay, Leonard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHeaman, E.A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLangford, Will, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMauduit, Julien, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMauduit, Julien, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMcKay, Ian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcNairn, Jeffrey L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPatrias, Carmela, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPilon, Dennis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSchrauwers, Albert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTillotson, Shirley, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTozer, Angela, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTunnicliffe, Jennifer, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTunnicliffe, Jennifer, e